At the end of the trade, the Prague stock exchange plunged into the negative
After the fall of Tuesday morning, the Prague Stock Exchange rectified its losses.
Transactions with <0xC4><0x8C>EZ shares accounted for almost half of the usual daily trades.
On Tuesday, from the beginning of the trade, the Prague stock exchange resumed with its fall from the previous day, when it lost almost six percent.
This time, the decline is due to the fall in shares on Wall Street.
The reaction of the market to the outcome of the vote of the US House of Representatives, which refused to adopt the stabilization plan of the US financial sector, is thus also noticeable in our country.
Falling Stocks in Asia
The Asian stock markets experienced a dramatic drop on Tuesday, even though the indexes managed, over the course of the day, to wipe out some of the losses.
The Hang Seng index of the Hong Kong Stock Exchange lost four percent during trades, but later wiped out some of the losses and reduced the decline to nearly 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index following the Hong Kong Stock Exchange’s Chinese equities movement lost 3.8 percent, with markets closed in Shanghai.
The shares of the Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent, but eventually we managed to reduce the losses to 4.3 percent.
According to its index, the Taiwan Stock Exchange lost 3.6 percent.
"Hesitation about bailout in the U.S. will affect financial markets around the world," noted Joseph Yam, the head of the Hong Kong Monetary Office.
Although Hong Kong is part of China, it establishes its own monetary policy, i.e. independently of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as in the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, U.S. lawmakers should quickly resume negotiations and adopt the financial system’s support proposal.
Otherwise, other countries would be at risk of being affected.
The bloodbath of American actions
On Monday, the US House of Representatives rejected the project to support the financial system, which it should have spent up to 700 billion dollars (nearly 12 billion K<0xC4><0x8D>).
The lawmakers thus denied the call for support for President George Bush’s project.
According to Bush, the project should solve the main causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
U.S. stocks were in a bloodbath on Monday, and the main stock indexes experienced the biggest drop in the last 20 years.
The Dow Jones lost nearly seven percent, having fallen to such a magnitude for the last time in 1987.
The index was already lost during the vote, but when it appeared that the proposal was not adopted, it was in free fall.
Congress Surrenders: U.S. Government Can Inject $700 Billion into Banks
The leaders of the U.S. Congress and the government of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of the financial aid agreement to the U.S. financial system.
It will be put to the vote early next week.
U.S. lawmakers made a decisive turn in the talks on the adoption of a rescue plan in the form of financial assistance in the amount of $700 billion (about 12 trillion crowns), granted to the U.S. financial system.
Success, however, is not certain.
Indeed, before the final version of the law can be published and put to the vote, Congressmen must complete a number of details of the agreement.
The financial system support plan will be reviewed in the House of Representatives on Monday.
Barney Frank, the chairman of the House Banking and Financial Regulation Committee, told Reuters on Sunday.
According to sources, on Wednesday at the earliest, the plan should a priori be put to the vote in the Senate.
According to economists, the announcement that the rescue plan will be adopted should be a major psychological first factor in reviving financial markets.
However, given the complexity of the mechanisms by which aid to markets can be effective, there will be "disillusionment".
Paulson: The plan must be effective
“We have made great progress.
We have settled our differing views on what form the package of measures for market stabilisation should take," Democrat Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg.
According to her, the final vote could be held as early as Sunday.
On Saturday night, lawmakers met with U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson to give the government a final shape.
It should buy from financial corporations the unsellable real estate assets that lead financial firms into considerable losses and threaten the stability of the system as a whole.
“We are about to agree on a plan that will work and that must also be effective in the market.
We still need to continue this market recovery plan, but I think we’re there,” Paulson said.
A signal for Asian trade
The global financial crisis has a considerable impact on falling stock markets.
According to the Democratic senator, if Harry Reid escapes, lawmakers are making sure that Congress comes to a final agreement as early as Sunday.
They want to calm investors ahead of the start of trading in Asian financial markets, which are located in the first time zone, where Congress’ decision could affect Monday’s trades.
For the moment, it is impossible to say with certainty when the two houses of the US Congress will proceed to the vote, or whether the negotiations will not risk being blocked, at the last moment, by this or that problem.
The legislators hope that it will be adopted in the coming days.
However, there will still be many changes to the law.
The total amount allocated to the system shall be divided into two parts.
The first $350 billion, as President George Bush wanted, should be available as soon as possible.
But if Congress gets the impression that the program is not doing its job, it has the option of blocking the granting of the remaining amount, by following two steps: first an additional $100 billion, and then, finally, $350 billion.
Mr. Bush hailed progress in the negotiations
Although the President may veto this decision, Congress has the option of holding the decision in the minority.
Despite these changes, the main idea of the program, which was to obtain finance for the redemption of bad real estate securities, whose value fell, because hundreds of thousands of Americans are unable to pay their mortgages, was maintained.
“All the work is done.
The House of Representatives should be able to pass the bill on Sunday, and the Senate on Monday," Republican Senator Judd Gregg said.
U.S. President George Bush himself is pleased with the progress in the negotiations.
His spokesman Tony Fratto said Bush was pleased with the progress made on Saturday and appreciated "the bipartisan effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy."
Limitation of golden parachutes
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, Chief Negotiator, says lawmakers have agreed on the responsibility of the financial program, protecting contributors from losses, the settlement of setbacks, the course of the plan on the timeline.
The new law also provides for the limitation of these golden parachutes for directors of companies participating in the program and establishes a committee, which will oversee the fund.
The latter should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
“We have worked very hard on the issue and made significant progress toward an agreement that will work and be effective for the market and for all Americans,” Paulson said.
The plan also provides assistance for property owners, who have trouble paying.
The government should negotiate new installments in the case of mortgages it will buy back, while decreasing the monthly payments of debtors and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: A psychological aid
According to Patria Finance chief economist David Marek, the proposed plan is a good idea, but its implementation will be very difficult.
“And that’s because we don’t know what the mechanism and price of buying up troubled assets will be.
This point will be decisive in deciding on the sharing of losses between the financial sector and the government," Marek told iHNed.cz this week.
Whether the plan will be adopted now, or early next week, is, according to Marek, not as important as that.
“It is much more important that Congressmen agree, as of this week, that they support this plan and that they dedicate it as soon as possible.
This psychological significance of the agreement, providing for the adoption of the plan, matters most at this time," Marek said.
A push to the extreme: MP3 players against mobiles.
We will advise you, how to choose
While virtually all mobiles can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make phone calls.
It seems clear that it is better to buy only a phone.
It does not prevent that there are sufficient reasons to acquire an independent reader.
The choice depends entirely on the mode of use and the requirements of the future owner.
It would be absurd to buy for the house an expensive high-end gramophone to put the new album of Maxim Turbulenc.
On the one hand, such musical products do not come out on vinyl, and from the point of view of quality, there is no objective reason for this to happen.
Now, if there are vinyl records crammed in your shelves, with art rock, jazz or blues, you probably dream of at least such a gramophone.
The same is true of music on the move, namely compressed music, to put it simply - MP3 music.
Here too, there are categories depending on price and quality.
For one, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a reader, in the same way that a Pink Floyd fan would have trouble with earphones purchased for twenty crowns on the market.
These are two extremes, between which there is enough room for everyone.
The choice is wide.
The battery life is also crucial.
Some high-end music players are capable of much more than just playing music, but these are unknown features, of course, of most mobiles.
No current device is as universal as the phone.
In addition to the primary functions, phone calls and sending SMS, it is able to read music and movies, record the latter, it has a variable quality camera and can, for example, even be used for navigation.
And if we take into account smartphones and communicators, you will have a small computer in your pocket.
Since no refrigerator can grill meat and no TV will take pictures, we are practically witnessing a miracle.
However, the universal character of the mobile is not without drawbacks.
The larger the number of functions you use, the smaller the interval between two recharges.
And playing music is one of the most important energy gophers.
Rarely are mobile phones that are able to play music for ten to twelve hours, in most cases, this figure is significantly lower.
In this regard, music players (especially the most rudimentary) are significantly more efficient.
In the case of cheap mobile phones, expect them to play music for only a few hours.
If, in addition, you happen to call from time to time, get, to be sure, a second recharge for work - this is valid even for the more expensive devices.
The problem will not arise for MP3 players, which are capable, after a recharge, of a continuous operation of at least 9 hours, including the least efficient.
Another problem occurs when recording music in the mobile.
Unfortunately, that a limited part of the devices has a universal USB connector, especially since not all can be directly connected to the computer, without special software.
One can, of course, record music directly on the memory card, but few card readers know how to do it without reduction, given the tiny dimensions of the memory cards used in mobiles.
As far as drives are concerned, you don’t need any software, except for an exception (iPod).
Just fill in, through the USB connector, the music device from the computer.
Most mobiles and readers will themselves create a media library classified by the name of the performer, the title of the album, the style, or by the judgment of the user.
Some devices only display an index with a tree structure, like Windows Explorer, others are capable of both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
Readers are easier to manipulate, mobiles have more know-how
When choosing a concrete device, focus on the battery life, memory capacity, quality and type of sound output and, of course, the ease of control.
If the music is for you, essentially, a background noise and if in the day you will listen to it only for a limited time, for example by taking the tram, you just need any mobile reading the MP3.
Virtually all mobile devices are capable of this.
You don’t even have to pay too much attention to the music formats that the mobile or player is able to read.
All manage to play MP3 and the vast majority of the music that will reach you will have exactly this format.
It is one of the most widespread formats and apart from it, the vast majority of devices also manage to read WMA format music.
AAFC (a format used by Apple and its iPods) is less common.
High-end mobiles also allow, for example, the purchase of music online.
Simply visit the corresponding operator’s (or other provider’s) web pages from your mobile phone and purchase the song or album in question.
This service alone should be a compelling reason to get a musical piece of furniture.
The offer of operators is unfortunately miserable and in most cases it is limited to fast-made radio tubes.
The prices are not the lowest either.
Nevertheless, it is generally considered that this way of buying music (whether by GSM, internet, or even wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry their mobiles on themselves.
Whenever you want to listen to something, you just have to take the mobile out of your pocket, while you have forgotten your MP3 player at home.
However, it is also important if you still have headphones on you or a handsfree with connection.
If this is not the case, you can use the built-in speakers, which practically all mobiles have, but a minimum of MP3 players.
For many, the main advantage of musical mobiles is their price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand.
For a price of three four thousand crowns, you can have a walkman already very suitable.
However, in most cases, you will be limited by the lack of output for ordinary headphones.
The price of the best phones and the best equipped, also equipped with an entrance for ordinary headphones, does not exceed fifteen thousand.
Readers, on the other hand, have the advantage of having an easy command.
Really anyone manages to ensure the order of the most rudimentary readers - which do not necessarily correspond to the cheapest (see our choice).
A minimum of functions; and the similarity of the command with that of a cassette station, commonly used in the past, or a gramophone, is obvious.
There is no risk of a collision in the form of a randomly connected mobile internet, followed by a huge data transmission bill.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobiles (e.g. the Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for exchangeable memory cards (type M2, microSD, and so on).
Even taking into account the additional purchase of such a card, you will not exceed two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
The basic models in principle only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive ones come out even with 8 GB memory cards.
If you already own a mobile and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take a Cowon, a Creative, a Sony, a Samsung, an Emgeton, or an iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you should not spend more than 1,100 crowns.
If you are one of the more demanding listeners, choose specialized walkman-mobiles (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices are equipped with independent control keys for MP3, and thus the ease of control is closer to that of an independent MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, whose walkman series phones have the same user menu as separately sold MP3 players, is the one that went the farthest in this field.
The same service, in the same price category, but with memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours) higher, is provided by an MP3 player produced by one of the brands mentioned above.
A first virtual operator will win the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively advanced, with our operators offering virtually the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Despite this, we still lack something - a virtual operator, which would force conventional operators to lower prices.
It may not be missing for a long time.
We have already mentioned, on Mobil.cz, that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
The Czech Telecommunications Agency (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), which reported that the price of an SMS was higher in our country than in the rest of the Union, confirmed this.
Thus, following the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming charges, a paradoxical situation may occur - SMS sent from abroad will be for some customers of Czech mobile operators cheaper than in the country.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high, compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really like to get into the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, given that we still have three mobile networks and a penetration that far exceeds 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this, Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xA1>k, the President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Agency (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), who has repeatedly stated that in the Czech Republic there is no longer room for another operator, made a fuss with the operators.
It is probably true that a conventional operator with its own network apparently no longer has much luck (by the way, now it would be difficult to find frequencies).
However, there is still a possibility - a virtual operator.
It is precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that has led to a considerable drop in prices, to which, subsequently, conventional operators also had to react.
Yet, even before the advent of holiday troubles such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile, voices similar to those we hear today were heard in Britain.
However, it turned out that there was still room for such operators and that they could have a real success.
We do not have to go too far to find examples.
In February we informed you about the launch, in Poland, of the virtual operator Mobilking.
In just six months, this operator managed to gain more than 100 thousand customers and become the fifth operator in the country.
Let’s add that behind the Mobilking there is the financial group Penta, which owns, among other things, the U:fon in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more concrete target group.
For their operation to be effective, they need far fewer customers than a conventional operator.
They are, in fact, exempt from the relatively high costs of construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
This is how in the world, virtual operators profile themselves as low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often counterbalanced by a limited range of services.
For example, in the UK, Tesco Mobile offers SMS at least twice as cheap as its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, relying on an unusual target group can also be a good publicity stunt.
Indeed, this operator specifically targets men.
“Real men choose Mobilking – an operator they like and can trust,” says David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether such a concept would be likely to work in our country as well.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD>, spokesman for Vodafone, doubts: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
Especially since it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the supply of services."
In the Czech Republic, no chance, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations are not very encouraging.
The launch of Mobilking will take place in other countries in our area," said Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>kov<0xC3><0xA1>, spokeswoman for the financial group Penta, in a telephone interview with Mobil.cz.
It thus indirectly confirmed that operators in the Czech Republic were, in any case, not in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything possible so that a potential competitor can not appear.
The GTS Novera group, which would like to take a new step in order to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the field of enterprise customers, has not hidden, for quite some time, its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
“We are very keen to be able to offer our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have already negotiated this possibility several times with all Czech mobile operators.
With some, we have managed to move forward in the negotiations," said group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
The future may be promising.
According to unofficial information, it seems that we may be able to host the first virtual operator by the end of the year.
But for now, his creation is accompanied by total silence.
"At the moment, we do not estimate that there is room on the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is very specific compared to others.
At the moment, no subject with a complex and serious project in this area has contacted us," said Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88> of Telefonika O2's press department, in his statement to Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> said in a rare agreement with O2's statement: "We have not yet registered a viable and bilaterally advantageous project, which could serve as a basis."
“It is virtually excluded that a virtual operator will appear in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
To operate in such a limited period of time, we should have a concrete agreement now.”
Instead, Vodafone focuses its attention on fulfilling requests to obtain its own 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> says in this regard: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and especially in the area of shared costs and infrastructure.
This, in our opinion, means the most input from the customer’s point of view.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to discover a partner to set up a common network for a fast mobile internet.”
Responsible authorities: in consultation with operators
The approach of mobile operators is easily understandable, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would have led to a drop in prices and therefore a decrease in their profit.
What is the point of facilitating the emergence of such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, operators know how to hear each other as thieves at the fair. The chicane accompanying the creation of the U:fon also bears witness to this.
The greatest apparent pressure on the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> at the time of the creation of the U:fon was that exerted by the company T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> web pages.
But today, the U:fon is ready to be used as an argument not to accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> noted in this regard: "Competition in the mobile market has also recently been amplified by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the nature of the mobile market in RT, it is obvious that the entry of an additional player would subject him, and especially his services, to high requirements."
But given the attitude of the mobile operators here, the indifference of the Czech regulatory bodies seems disconcerting.
However, this is not just the attitude of the <0xC4><0x8C>TU, which, unlike Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately does not have the power in the Czech Republic to intervene in economic competition.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
However, the latter adopted, in the face of this problem, its typical position.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator in question regarding the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No agreement of this kind has been concluded at this time, as the supply of potential interested parties has a priori not shown sufficient interest for conventional operators," Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa from the Department of External Relations of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS said in response to our question.
A statement thus made would not be surprising from the operators' representatives.
But on the part of an office, which must represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, also take care that no one takes advantage of its position in the market, such a statement is more than confusing.
Even more so as Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa adds: "Foreignly, where virtual operators are normally present, it can be seen that their entry into the market has contributed to a drop in the prices of mobile phone services."
However, putting pressure in the direction of an honest functioning of the market and a fall in prices is apparently not in the interests of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
What is indeed shocking is the almost touching concord of the three mobile operators, which results from their reactions.
The question, whether this is really a coincidence, naturally arises.
In the same way, a price of gasoline that is strictly the same at all service stations is probably due to chance and the fierce competition.
"The Office has not detected any signs of anti-competitive behaviour in this regard, so it has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position, therefore none has an increased corresponding responsibility for its behaviour in the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile market to virtual operators are probably missing even from the telecommunications regulator," Chalupa said in a statement.
Interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many points of disagreement.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, according to which telecommunications is, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators has a dominant position in such a market.
However, some legal experts offer a different view of things: in order for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, it is necessary to obtain, each time, the consent of the network operator.
And the mobile operator has quite logically the monopoly on its network.
Thus, it necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of its activity.
However, even without admitting this argument, it should be at least worrying for the OHIM that three mobile operators are visibly proceeding in a similar manner.
However, the complaints of many interested parties (including GTS Novera, already mentioned) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
Bringing down responsibility on the <0xC4><0x8C>TU is a fairly common turn in communications, through which the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS washes its hands of the matter.
We have already encountered this type of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recent renewal of the Telecommunications Act, which was adopted recently, has not succeeded in extending the powers of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> in the area of economic competition in telecommunications, although many specialists have promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS must know this very well, but their interests are apparently elsewhere.
When no one is looking, it can work.
That said, the operation of some sort of pseudo-virtual operators, several in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies that publish their own price lists for mobile phone services, but the latter are only partially public.
In most cases, it is about companies dealing with multi-level marketing.
Custom mobile phone services are offered by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these firms usually reach only elected officials.
The magic trick is that the company in front of the operator is a classic company customer, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, she gets special (and other) price offers.
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such a resale.
“If what you are referring to were to happen, it could be a breach of the contractual conditions that we would examine and which could result in a cessation of collaboration with the company in question,” Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> said.
Nevertheless, it is quite unlikely that an echo of such an activity has not reached those responsible for mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, there may be thousands of customers.
No operator, however, is opposed to such a procedure.
Indeed, the activities of these firms bring them considerable profits, and, at the same time, as opposed to real virtual operators, they do not threaten them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> points out the possible problems: "The law allows such speculations, however, the services of these companies are used only by a negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they are forced to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not registered under their name, so they can not fully dispose of it, in the manner of ordinary customers of mobile operators."
But that is precisely what should seem strange to <0xC4><0x8C>TU.
In addition, there is another question to the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such a procedure, why do they block the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has relatively broad powers to be able to disclose such an activity, and if it does not wish to be satisfied with the explanations of the operators, who claim to have no idea that this would happen, their contractual conditions prohibit it.
When we will no longer be the most expensive country
As we have already mentioned several times, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought about a considerable decrease in the price of services.
However, in virtually all countries where virtual operators appeared, the classical operators sometimes tried more, sometimes less, to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were practically the same - a market too small, or even too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
However, it was precisely at this level that the regulatory bodies in the developed countries intervened, which defended not the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Both by formal measures and by informal pressure, they eventually obtained the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory agencies deal with this issue in the way of a hot potato that is disposed of by passing it on to a nearby target.
Following the experiences we have, we cannot get rid of the impression that the confusion in their skills is in these cases more than profitable.
But let's not throw the handle after the heist.
If the behind-the-scenes information is true and a virtual operator will appear soon, the Czech mobile market may be on the move.
If one of the operators has accepted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS can hardly remain impassive in the face of the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And perhaps we will stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four achievements of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, on the occasion of Czech Nationality Day, Prime Minister Mirek Topol<0xC3><0xA1>nek solemnly presented the new recordings of the national anthem Kde domov m<0xC5><0xAF>j (Where is my homeland?).
The anthem was again recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Ji<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xAD> B<0xC4><0x9B>lohl<0xC3><0xA1>vek.
We have four versions - with a male or female solo song, an interpretation with choir and an instrumental version.
The song is performed by Kate<0xC5><0x99>ina Kn<0xC4><0x9B><0xC5><0xBE><0xC3><0xAD>nkov<0xC3><0xA1> and Adam Plachetka.
Otakar Jeremiah and Jaroslav Kr<0xC4><0x8D>ek are the authors of the arrangements of the anthem.
You can listen to the four new versions on the iHNed.cz server.
B<0xC4><0x9B>lohl<0xC3><0xA1>vek considers Czech national song as one of the most beautiful hymns.
As he had previously confided to <0xC4><0x8C>esk<0xC3><0xBD> rozhlas (Czech public radio), he chose for the interpretation of solo versions of singers with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated.
"From the beginning, I tried to take care that both singers, as well as the choir, have a good diction, so that we understand the words well, that they sing simultaneously," he said.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Kde domov m<0xC5><0xAF>j first sounded in 1834 on the boards of Stavovské divadlo (the Theatre of the States) in Fidlova<0xC4><0x8D>ka (Kermesse des savetiers), an original Czech piece by Josef Kajet<0xC3><0xA1>n Tyl, accompanied by the music of Franti<0xC5><0xA1>ek <0xC5><0xA0>kroup.
It has become popular and people have spontaneously appropriated it.
After the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918, the first couplet naturally became an integral part of the national anthem.
It remained one of the seven national symbols even after the creation of the independent Czech Republic.
