Insomnia Nights for Hypo Real Estate Shareholders
The German banking system is relatively stable, the Federal Minister of Finance insisted just a few weeks ago.
What a chance that the politician used the word <0x60>relatively' and that he slipped that the German banking sector would not be spared by the movements of crisis.
This one actually happened this weekend.
The Bavarian real estate financier Hypo Real Estate (HRE), alongside DAX, gets a $1 billion loan from a consortium of German banks to protect itself from market turbulence.
A person familiar with the situation told Reuters on Monday that aid credits are being issued for up to <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>35 billion.
The Hypo Real Estate should now pay interest on the fraction to which it would thus be entitled.
The money comes from private banks as well as from public-law banks.
In the background, it is the company-daughter Depfa that bears the losses.
The state financier had, according to a newspaper article, refinanced himself in the very short term for long-term projects for which he had borrowed money - which is no longer possible because of mistrust of the markets.
In the first half of 2008, the bank's liquidity reserve had been reduced from 95 percent to 2.37 million euros, the equity rate had also slightly decreased from 1.6 to 1.45 percent.
Current and net earnings from financial transactions had fallen to zero compared to the same period the previous year, earnings from the allocation of receivables and determined securities as well as the termination of provisions in credit operations had fallen by more than 70 per cent to 5 million euros.
And it is only thanks to the significant profits from the reimbursement of the downstream accounting costs resulting from the restructuring of the former Depfa group, as well as the reimbursement of interest according to the book of tax procedures and commercial purchases for Konzern’s companies that the deficit in earnings of about 16 percent turned out to be mod.
After its privatization in 1990, the former state financier had at first speculated poorly on industrial real estate loans, which had then been branched out to Aareal bank.
Because conventional state financing was not sufficiently cost-effective, Depfa then engaged more intensively in infrastructure projects and in the financing of joint projects between private and state investors (Private-Public-Partnership, PPP) and diversified internationally.
On the value of the subsidiary, the Hypo Real Estate must make amortizations that should have on the calculation of the gains and losses of the group an essential material effect that still remains rather vague.
The fact is that the dividends have been amputated.
By 2007, they had already been truncated to two-thirds.
Since the acquisition of Depfa, Hypo Real Estate has been a highly important state and infrastructure investor.
It is stronger than other institutions dependent on refinancing in the interbank market as it has no customer deposits.
With the bankruptcy of investment bank Lehman Brothers two weeks ago, the allocation of credits between banks has again increased considerably, as banks have accumulated their liquidity.
The Hypo Real Estate needs a short-term means of refinancing for part of the total amount of Depfa's loans - approximately 50 billion euros - annually.
According to a statement from Hypo Real Estate, the group’s need for financing is covered with medium-term credit and the company is protected from the influence of international financial markets largely out of business at the moment.
Other sources say the refinancing would be secured through the funds until the end of 2009.
HRE Chairman Georg Funke, on the other hand, explained that the Hypo Real Estate group should no longer have to resort to financial markets in the medium term.
The Federal Bank and the Federal Financial Services Supervisory Authority (Bafin) assume that Hypo Real Group’s market capacity is now secured.
The shareholders and creditors of the bank have only to hope for.
However, given the dynamics and weightlessness of the crisis, there is no certainty.
It is also not inconceivable that funding should not be used to its full extent.
But the opposite cannot be ruled out either.
After the fact that the bank is, according to the latest announcements, still on the verge of insolvency on Sunday evening, this rescue, at least provisionally, will not succeed in reassuring the minds either.
The share price fell from 75 percent to 3.30 euros.
On the other hand, bond prices are doing particularly well.
While debt in the first place has barely moved, the prices of second-tier loans are dwindling.
The most affected are mainly the investment funds of the former W<0xC3><0xBC>rttemberg subsidiary Hypo and those of course that have a life beyond 2009.
The bonds of the Hypo Real Estate bank previously seemed to be an alternative speculation investment, now their value must be considered dependent on the stability of the international banking system after the net hardening of the banking crisis and the crisis of the institution itself that brought the crisis into the establishment by the purchase of the bank Deffa.
As long as the issuing institutes, governments and commercial banks are still willing to support the system, it is possible to assume a resorption of arrears over time.
Or it will happen what no one dares to hope at the moment - that the financial crisis can be overcome in the next 15 months.
But in the face of the renewed noises of partial nationalization, the probability that was approaching certainty has now become a mere well-founded hope.
This should set aside sleepless nights primarily for long-term creditors on deciding whether to separate themselves from their commitments.
Short-term investors can still use what they have drawn a line on to constitute a deferral of losses for the next few years on the next capital income tax from automatically-drawn stock gains.
