The rats also have sensations.
A rat or a cockroach flees from danger, does that mean he also feels fear?
The neurophysicist Joseph LeDoux is convinced of this: many animals also have sensations.
But how can we verify that he feels the same way when he behaves the same way as we do?
In the online magazine "Edge", contributions have been published for several years by famous scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series of articles answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else having been able to prove it until now just as we cannot prove that other human beings have a consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope that all human brains have the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and address the issues of feeling or consciousness in general, we enter hard-to-perform terrain because the Hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: it kills, flees, or attacks.
Humans behave in the same way, which is why some scientists deduce a comparable subjective experience.
However, I do not believe it.
Two aspects of the structure of the brain make the transposition of our experience subjective to that of animals difficult.
One aspect is that the circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the prefrontal lateral cortex (due to its participation in short-term memory and in the functions of direction and execution).
This vast region is much more developed in humans than in other primates and appears to be entirely absent in other beings.
At the very least for these aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, among which the consciousness of who we are, and the ability to predict and decide, it is reasonable to assume that the human being is even different from other primates.
Another significant peculiarity could lie in the linguistic nature of man: a large part of his existence being related to language, it often means that his consciousness depends on it.
In this case, the animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness were not to depend on language, it would surely influence it, so that animal consciousness, no matter how it is produced, would probably differ greatly from most of our states of consciousness.
This is why it is so difficult to determine what consciousness may look like in other animals.
If this, internal and subjective, does not allow itself to be measured or, because of this particular Hardware, analyzed based on our own experience, then its observation poses big problems for us.
Most of my developments refer to the content of conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness that should be more easily accessible scientifically.
Animal consciousness processes could be examined without regard to their content, and this is exactly what happened during studies on the short-term memory of primates, particularly with the example of visualization.
But in this approach followed by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, we focus more on the nervous correlations of consciousness than on causal mechanisms: both may or may not be the same.
Curiously, this approach also highlights the weight of the prefrontal cortex in the realization of visualization.
But what does that mean for the emotions?
I conclude that an emotional system such as that of fear is activated in a brain conscious of its own activity.
What we call “fear” is therefore the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the localized defense system in the brain (or its aftermath, such as the body’s reactions) takes hold of vivid memory.
Thus observed, emotions are closely related to the regions of the cortex that characterize primates and especially humans.
Subtle degrees of feeling, associated with our volatile nature, emerge, because we can, with the help of words and grammar, differentiate and categorize states to impute them to others than ourselves.
On the other hand, Antonio Damasio, for example, thinks that sensations from primitive activities arise in the regions of the cortical sensation of the cortex and the brain stem, just as Jaak Pankseep who, however, focuses more on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it could quite participate in transversal sensations of any kind.
From a purely theoretical point of view, I cannot contradict it, but I believe this is inescapable.
Pankseep argues that what appears as fear in humans and rats is probably also felt as such in both cases: how can one still verify whether rats and humans feel the same way when they behave in a similar way?
A cockroach flees from danger, but what if he feels fear?
In my view, similar behaviours are not enough to prove identical experiences.
Certainly, the nervous comparison helps: rats and humans have similar brain trunks, cockroaches, on the other hand, do not even have a brain.
But is the brain stem the cause of the sensations?
And even if we could prove it for humans, how could we prove it in rats?
I think rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?) have sensations.
But I don't know how to prove it.
And because their sensations are probably completely different from ours (since human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I prefer to explore emotional behavior than emotional sensations of rats.
In any case, progress is nerve-wracking to the extent that the same is measured in rats and in humans.
Since I do not explore language and consciousness in rats, nor sensations, I do not know if they exist.
We could judge this as short-term, but I prefer to move forward rather than constantly bumping into a wall.
I am an emotional pragmatist.
