"I photograph the master outside the scene to capture elements of his character" G<0xC3><0xBC>nther Bauer - Photographer
No heels, no starry-eyed clothes.
The essence of the great masters of flamenco, freed from all tensions to obtain the relaxed appearance of man or woman.
On the one hand, the artist.
On the other, the person.
Inseparable except in privacy, in these moments unknown to the general public, where we discover intimate gestures and stolen eyes of artists who do not care to get on stage.
The German G<0xC3><0xBC>nther Bauer mixes in "Flamenco - people" the theatricality of a few scenes with singers, dancers and guitarists with this less known side of the artists.
In this project, the photographer takes up the particular iconography of flamenco from different angles.
Included in the programming of the Month of Flemish Photography, the exhibition "reflects the international importance of flamenco, greater every day", explains the creator, who clarifies that "Flamenco - people" "can be anyone but, after seeing the photos, the observer realizes that these are not typical images of artists on stage.
These people photographed "in the street" are artists capable of conveying passion, sadness, joy on stage ... by captivating the public.
To capture moments of personality of these artists you do not have to take photos on stage.
They have a personality and a character of their own.
What interested me was to create an intimate atmosphere that allows me to capture with the camera the moments of personality of the flamenco stars.”
With the festival "Chant populaire des Mines", Bauer began in 1997 a long journey to photograph singers, guitarists or dancers with a plate camera.
These are portraits that, thanks to the choice of the camera and the material, recalls classical photography.
The implementation of different stylistic means breaks with the classic side of the image, giving it a touch of modernity, this reflects the perception of flamenco according to Bauer: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and that surprises every day".
It is not about dance or singing in itself, but about the personality and character of the artist who captivates the public with his art.
The search for the essentials and magic has been the constant of this work that is presented these days at the gallery El Fot<0xC3><0xB3>mata.
Flamenco stars such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are part of the selection made from about seventy photographed artists.
The project turned into an anthology of flamenco, which will soon be published in a book collection of portraits exhibited at the gallery.
Bauer's passion for portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with the "Portraits de vieux sportifs" ("SportARTproject").
Although the concepts are different in "Flamenco - people", the photographer admits that he loves to photograph the portrait of people, to know them and to be able to enter their lives for a more or less long moment.
I believe that in photography, portraiture is the most difficult genre.
You find yourself in front of people, characters that sometimes you don’t know or that leave you only a few minutes to take a picture of them.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to make my ideas come true.”
This collection of portraits of the current flamenco entitled "Flamenco - people", is on display at the Galerie El Fot<0xC3><0xB3>mata, located at number 20 de la Mata street (parallel street to the People's House of Hercules) which will be open until October 16.
