Free opinion - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Speech
In its September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Executive Vice President of Canadian Mining Barrick Gold.
Pursuing an Orwellian logic, he claims that the world's largest gold company has attempted a defamation lawsuit of six million against three authors and a small publishing house without the money in order to launch a "transparent public debate".
While it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in defamation cases, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely obscured by Mr. Garver.
For, for Barrick Gold, would the best way to conduct a public debate be to ruin anyone who dares to support a position contrary to his own?
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and the publisher of the Black Book of Canada will have to spend considerable sums to prepare their defense and fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers backed by the almost bottomless pockets of the mine.
The tactic, in these unequal struggles, is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose a friendly settlement that will wink at the opposition in addition to scaring anyone who dares to look at the issue again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, she should have presented her vision of the facts to the public.
Contrary to what is happening in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are normally held through the exchange of ideas and not by batons.
It was therefore sufficient for the mining company to open its books, files and establish a real debate, through newspapers, the media, publications and the funding of independent research teams that could have shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to trust public opinion and dismisses petitions and letters of support to the authors of Black Canada.
Perhaps Mr. Garver could explain how he can both ask for a "public" debate while disregarding the views of that same public?
In the vice-president's world, it seems that this word refers only to fat-paid lawyers and not to all Canadians; here is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In a democracy, even detractors have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold doesn't understand - or doesn't want to understand - is that the public that supports the authors and publishers of Black Canada does so primarily because it rejects the brutal way of mining.
This audience is ready to hear Barrick and to judge, but on the basis of civilized exchanges of arguments, and not in the context of what many perceive as a gag chase (following the "public debate", Barrick Gold has also just filed a statement in the place of the authors of Black Canada intimidating them).
Beyond Mr. Garver’s surreal speech, Barrick Gold’s prosecution is a direct attack on academic research freedom and the pursuit of truth, essential to any democratic society.
It denies the right to quote from credible sources and to debate facts and interpretations, which are the very basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss topics that displease the rich companies of this world in a country like Canada, under penalty of repeated prosecution, who will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could do so by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Black Canada.
She has a right of reply.
The academic community, to which we belong, has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s disproportionate pursuit clearly shows that, contrary to what she claims, she has no desire for a transparent debate.
This is a loss for the academic world, as well as for public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place mechanisms to limit such abusive prosecutions.
Wall Street Rescue Operation - Democrats and Republicans agree on a deal
The Bush administration and the leaders of Congress, both Republicans and Democrats, finally came to an agreement yesterday on the biggest economic bailout plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan to curb the financial crisis that has rocked Wall Street for months is yet to be approved by both houses of Congress.
It provides for, inter alia: better control by elected officials of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of public money committed, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for lack of payment, as well as a right to look at the salaries paid to the executives of the rescued companies.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi, and Republican Representative at the negotiating table Senator Judd Gregg announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday, at the end of a two-day negotiating marathon.
"We have made great progress toward an agreement that will be effective in the markets," Bush administration spokesman Henry Paulson said.
“Everything has been done to shield the real economy and ordinary Americans from the ongoing crisis on Wall Street,” she said.
“That’s the fundamental point: if we don’t do that, the trauma, chaos and disruption to the daily lives of Americans will be immense,” said Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had turned to the sprint in the last few hours for fear of the effect that a new failure would have on the mood of investors.
The deadline that had been agreed was the opening of the markets this morning.
Lately associated with the negotiations, the two candidates in the US presidential election have been rather supportive of the agreement, without failing to express their displeasure that we are forced to reach this end.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has attributed the addition of certain provisions to the agreement, including those aimed at allowing homeowners to keep their homes and those on the salaries of executives of state-run businesses.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is nothing to be congratulated on.
But these measures are necessary," he said on US television.
Asked on another channel whether he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, responded, "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so."
“The big lines I’ve read [show] that it’s something that we’re all going to have to digest and that we’re going to be able to move forward with.
The option of doing nothing is simply not acceptable,” he said.
The $700 billion plan aims to buy back with taxpayers’ money the dubious, risky, and unsellable debts of U.S. financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis triggered by the bursting of a real estate bubble that first led to the collapse of risky mortgage loans (subprimes) before expanding to other more widespread forms of credit securities (PCAAs) and leading to a freeze of liquidity and bank outflows.
It is a group of elected Republicans who had the first draft of the agreement overturned last week.
It is believed to have come out of this deadlock since Democrats agreed that certain “toxic” assets of struggling companies are only insured by the government, rather than bought.
In order to round out the angles for everyone in Congress, a provision was also added that if the government were to assume losses for five years with this program, it could put in place new taxes to help it recover its stake.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first tranche of $250 billion to which an additional $100 billion may be added if the president deems it necessary.
The payment of another $350 billion is expected to be endorsed by another Congressional vote.
In exchange for his help, Washington will get shares in the relief companies that will earn him dividends in case of profit and that he will be able to resell when the torment has passed.
The federal government will have the opportunity to delay seizure procedures for housing attached to real estate loans covered by this plan, as well as to set limits on the remuneration and severance payments paid to the managers of the affected companies.
The architects of the plan would like to see it submitted to the vote of the House of Representatives today, and to that of the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will have the green light.
Votes continued to rise against this project yesterday, both in the Republican and Democratic camps.
“Obviously, Washington doesn’t hear you,” said Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee.
“Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the one that benefits the taxpayers.”
Animator of a small group in Congress dubbed "the caucus of skeptics", Democratic Representative Brad Sherman presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred prominent economics professors, including three Nobel Prize winners, have written to us to tell us: Congress is being asked not to hurry and to carefully examine the path to take," he said.
At the same time, in Europe, we once again had proof of the global nature of the crisis.
At the end of an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the banking group Fortis for 11.2 billion euros (16.3 billion US).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg had been made necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it was giving up acquiring its competitor in the middle of a shipwreck since it lost 2 billion euros (2.9 billion US) in the crisis of risky real estate loans in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of the 20 largest European banks and 10 largest insurers.
"This is not money lost," Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
In return, one regains a right to vote in the bank and influence.
It’s precisely something that savers and households now appreciate that times are looking uncertain.”
Meanwhile, on the other side of the Channel, the British government appeared to be nationalizing another bank battered by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would take over all the current loans from the Bradford and Bringley bank, including more than 41 billion (US$75.5 billion) of real estate loans.
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it would buy the branches and customer accounts of the British bank.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank, after Northern Rock, that the British government should nationalize since the beginning of this financial crisis.
