The psychology of over-the-counter: why do we spend more money?
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate the merchandise.
Researchers in neurology and economics at the University of New York have managed to update the neurological and economic foundations of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, humans do not want to be distanced during this type of competition, such as an auction on eBay, and that is why they even prefer to pay too high a price.
These researches have attempted to draw up a neurological scheme of this kind of "game" using experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lottery, while the other group took part in a playful auction, while using a functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) process, the researchers analyzed the active brain domains of experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could earn money, but during the auction, an essential element of which is the over-sale of a third, the whole being under the brain stem, called the striatum, was moving intensively during the loss of the game.
This part of the brain, in addition to several other functions, plays a role in the mechanism of "self-stimulation" of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the rise in prices is explained by the flight from the violent reaction of the striatum.
In support of their theories, the economic members of this group of researchers continued financial monitoring analyses.
In these cases, three groups outperformed one partner under various circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product in question, and so they made their placement.
To another group, they promised that if, in addition, they came out winning the game, then they would receive an additional $15, as a reward.
While the third group received the 15 dollars before the auction, the members of the group also lost that money, in case they lost the auction.
The difference between these two groups is in fact that the emphasis was on one on victory, while the other on failure.
By proving the neurologists' hypothesis, the team members of the players "against failure" were willing to bet higher than those made by the control group and the group "for victory".
“These results cannot be demonstrated by any existing economic theory.
Indeed, each of them explained the phenomena observed during auctions only through the pleasure of winning and the parade in front of the risk.
Only the methods of neurological imaging have helped to remove the contradiction between the two theories by now leading to a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, a professor in the Faculty of Economic Sciences at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: when should we see a doctor?
Around the world, about half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary, chronic liver disease is mentioned among the leading causes of death.
One hundred miles are estimated to be the sick carriers of the hepatitis virus in Hungary, but only seven miles follow a treatment. This is due to the fact that often patients do not know that they are carriers of the virus.
The name hepatitis is a generic name given to infections affecting the liver and caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and jaundice are characteristic, but the pathogens and diseases generated differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, according to the pathogenic genes, spread mainly in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (for example: contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through the blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
For travelers, it is recommended to get vaccinated against viruses A and B. There is no vaccine against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after consumption of contaminated food, in general, accompanied by poor general condition, weakness, stomach aches and nausea.
Then develops on the skin and on the white of the eye a visible jaundice, the stools become lighter and the urine takes a darker color. The healing can take two to three weeks.
Around the world, every year, one million people die from the most serious form of this pathology, such as cancer or cirrhosis of the liver caused by hepatitis B.
The main cause of this is that it is estimated that only one in ten patients receives medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients do not know how to get the virus, because the pathogenic gene subverts the cells of the liver. In many cases, the first symptoms appear only after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular screening tests.
Contamination is much higher than the average among a population of three groups: people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and tattooed people.
Currently, there are 200 million patients with chronic hepatitis C worldwide.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult your doctor as soon as symptoms of unknown origin are observed.
The disease can be cured, if it is detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, in this way the risk of infection disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, first organized in 2004 by organizations representing patients from all over the world.
Its goal is to draw attention to chronic liver cirrhosis, caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
Does the one who grows in God feel less pain?
According to the results of recent research, religious belief would function as a kind of painkiller, which would have already contributed to making the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
The British newspaper Telegraph published an article according to which researchers from the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment by analyzing at what level belief in God could influence tolerance to human pain.
As part of this experience, at least bizarre, 12 Catholic believers and as many atheists were subjected to electroshock, while each of them was observing a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude a large part of the suffering.
Thanks to a technique of palpation of the human brain, it was also found that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain responsible for the regulation of pain.
This analysis is the first in a series of experiments in which academics, scholars, philosophers and theologians from different sectors of the university participate.
More precisely, the experiment is carried out as follows: an instrument emitting sparks and scattering electroshocks is fixed on the left hand of the experimental subject.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to look at two paintings in a sustained way, one being the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and the other, the Lady in Hermine painted by Leonardo da Vinci in the 15th century.
The researchers at the origin of this experience hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary evokes a kind of state of faith among believers, while the choice of Da Vinci's painting, not very different from the first one, was about its soothing effect.
The experimental subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and during that time, received 20 electroshocks in four parts succeeding each other, while watching either the religious-themed painting or the more general-themed one.
Catholics said that in the sight of the Virgin Mary, they felt like they were “safe,” like someone who was “taken care of” and they “calm down, and peace has invaded them.”
At the sight of the religious-themed painting, they reported 12% less pain than when they looked at Leonard's work.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself took part in the experiment, thinks that one can achieve the same effects with any other strong image, in atheists, provided one finds the appropriate photo.
"We should find an image that they react very positively to, such as a mother or a father," the psychologist said.
Tom Wright, the Anglican bishop, welcomed the results of this research.
“The practice of faith should change, and in many cases, it actually changes our personality,” Wright said.
After these excellent results, all that remains is the question of what would be the effect on the regulation of the pain of the subjects if we show the believers a Madonna painted by Leonard or by a painter of the same caliber?
Would the sight of a better Virgin Mary lead to better results?
