The intelligent car imitates the flight of the bumblebee
What method would be better to develop technologies capable of avoiding an obstacle, if it is not the imitation of an obstacle detector already existing in nature?
For example, bees.
In the amazing project presented at CEATEC, taking place in Japan, the buzzing bees gave Nissan engineers the strategic starting point, to inspire them on how to design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built a mini robot car, a bio-inspired self-robot control system, type BR23C, which it has equipped with the qualities of bees, the ultimate goal being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
During its flights, each bee constitutes its own space, oval in shape, which in reality, looks very much like our safe protective shell - explained Kazuhhiro Doi, the director of the research and development and technological public relations department of the brand at the exhibition.
The bee's faceted eye plays a vital role, as it is able to see in all directions, at an angle of 300 degrees.
To mimic the functions of the faceted eye, the engineers approached the idea of the laser rangefinder.
It identifies the obstacles at an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 meters in front of the BR23C, it evaluates the distances and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which turns it into an avoidance maneuver immediately.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then, the mini auto robot, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it at an angle sufficient to avoid collision.
Unlike any system currently in existence, this avoidance maneuver takes place entirely instinctively.
“If not, the mini auto robot could not react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle,” says Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotic car project.
It must react instinctively and instantly, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and internal layer of the protective envelope, a layer where for the moment the collision is considered inevitable.
This whole process must reflect what the bee is doing to avoid the other bees.
The process must take place in the blink of an eye.
Unlike bees, the difference can not go up, down or diagonally, it can only be of two dimensions, and only in the direction in which the wheels can turn.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that bees possess to avoid the other bees, in our case, we could only use rotational movement, acceleration as well as deceleration as maneuvers available to the mini auto robot
The BR23C uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy concentration, which makes their life longer than in the lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the instinctive intelligent reaction that is paramount, not the processing of data, let alone the ability to store.
This mechanism must process only a few incoming signals per second, and react to them.
It is not necessary to store them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers. In this way, it uses only a few dozen kilobytes of continuous memory.
There is no need for a memory capacity of gigabytes, or even megabytes.
This is the first step towards the design of an instant-avoidance technology, which Nissan estimates will enter mass-produced cars in the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles on his way.
