Industrial prices have continued to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month, and by 12.9 per cent compared to August 2007 - reports the Central Statistical Office of Hungary.
Industrial export sales prices increased by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008, while compared to the previous year, they decreased by 3.9 per cent.
As a result of fluctuations in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent compared to the previous month, and by 3.2 per cent compared to the previous year.
Domestic industrial sales prices increased only to a lesser extent: by 0.1 per cent, compared to the previous month.
The domestic sales prices of the processing industry sectors have only experienced a slight increase of the order of 0.1 per cent compared to July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the leather goods and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8 per cent), with firstly the manufacture of bags and belts with a monthly increase of 4.6 per cent, then the production of shoes with a monthly increase of 2.5 per cent.
The higher level of plastic and chemical raw material prices has resulted in a considerable monthly increase in the prices of the chemical and product manufacturing sector (1.6 per cent).
Deflation has resulted in the oil processing (1.4 per cent), the manufacture of electrical machinery and appliances (0.9 per cent), and a minimal increase in the wood processing sector (0.1 per cent).
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing activities have not changed.
Other sectors in the processing industry saw an increase, ranging from 0.2 percent to 0.9 percent.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors, which account for a significant share of domestic industrial production, prices rose by 0.3 per cent in August, mainly due to the effect of the increase in the price of gas set up by the authorities since 1 July.
In a 12-month comparison, taking into account the domestic sales of the processing sectors, the prices of the oil processing sector experienced the most significant increase (32.4 per cent).
In the metallurgical manufacturing sector, prices increased by 13.2 per cent, while in the important area of food, beverage and tobacco production, prices increased by 11 per cent.
Price declines occurred in the textile and textile products (2.5 per cent) and machinery and electrical appliances (0.3 per cent) sectors.
In the other sectors of the processing industry, price increases ranged from 0.6 per cent to 9.1 per cent.
In the entire processing industry, prices increased by 10.2 per cent over the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors exceeded those of the previous year by 18.7 per cent.
Among the domestic trade groups and according to the allocation of sectors, in August, it was the investment profit-making sectors that showed the most significant monthly price increase (0.7 per cent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, while those in the energy and material-producing sectors destined for further processing did not experience any change compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, there was the largest increase in the energy and material production sectors for further processing (16.8 per cent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, inflation was measured at 6.8 per cent, while for the profit-making sectors, inflation was measured at 1.4 per cent.
Export sales prices of the industrial sector, in HUF, increased by 1.1 percent in August compared to the previous month, while they suffered a decrease of 3.9 percent over 12 months.
In one month, our national payment method has weakened by 1.7 per cent against the euro, and 7.1 per cent against the dollar. Compared to August 2007, it has strengthened by 7.5 per cent against the euro and by 15.9 per cent against the dollar.
