And so, it is from the government of each state that everyone expects interventions, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and above all a fondness for credits: when one goes through a difficult period, there are only the states that have the economic resources, the mass of financial resources capable of trying to put things back in place.
They also have the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of inestimable value, elements that no international market or organization can ever dispose of in a similar way.
This new emphasis of the nation-state crisis is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the ever-greater importance that the more recent economic developments of the economy tend to attribute to a factor quite related to this element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, indeed, when we were convinced that we were now entering the kingdom of the network, of increasingly sophisticated technology, of the non-material, convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we realized one thing at a time, that our future will have to pay more and more.
Things that can certainly be transported from one place to another of the earth, but which are absolutely linked to a confined space, to a territory.
Thus, who is sovereign, certainly has more cards than he who is not, that is, he who has the misfortune of living in a place without harvest, without oil and without water.
I now come to the second novelty which, however, foresees a fracture.
Who says Territory, State, Government, inevitably said Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this respect, the economic crisis seems to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective need for authoritarian leadership, the search for a person who knows how to take control of the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for existing leaderships, economic species that have proved inadequate and full of shadow area.
And moreover, something even deeper, in a certain sense, even disturbing: a discredit, a suffering, an image of inadequacy, a feeling of alienation that tends to involve the entire class of directors in a growing number of Western countries.
Thus the conviction of the various classes increases even more, before the actions are the same ideas of the social elites until now at their peak, their way of listening and being, their culture in the complex acceptance of the term, to have the same time, and to be always more alien to the opinions of the majorities.
In short, the demand for leadership, feeds underground, a powerful and branched movement of delegitimizations of the ruling classes and the traditional political orders, which manifest themselves in the "revolts" of the improvised elections or, in the changes of collective moods of the latter of recent times, from the rise of the conservatives in Austria to the rise of the conservatives.
One has the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their format, one would say, are always more difficult, which does not date from today, to understand and therefore to represent the deep layers of Western societies, and that the economic crisis is potentially intensifying and increasing.
In view of all this, talking about a current "rebellion of the masses" on the agenda seems frankly exaggerated.
