The superglue to walk on the walls.
Overcome the laws of gravity with a super glue and, in the future, walk on the walls like Spiderman.
This is the goal of various American research centers, and today, a team of four institutes has almost succeeded.
With an adhesive measuring just 2.5 square centimetres, the researchers managed to keep a 100-kilogram body glued to a vertical wall.
The American journal Science has published the findings of some researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material, invented by the team of researchers, is an evolution of those we know who use a particular carbon structure, called carbon nanotubes.
"The glue principle can be imagined as a series of tubes arranged like a stack of spaghetti," explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
Scientists have been inspired by the legs of the geckos, covered with microscopic hairs that allow to ensure the animal, a perfect adherent.
Tests on various materials, such as glass, Teflon, and glass paper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times more powerful than the legs of these reptiles, and at the same time, that it “is easily detached from the wall,” explains Liming Dai, a researcher at the Faculty of Engineering at Dayton University.
“This material could be used as a temporary adhesive,” adds Liming Dai.
Maybe to walk on walls like Spiderman? Maybe yes, but researchers think of a much less fascinating use such as the connection between electronic devices, since carbon nanotubes are conductors of heat and electric current.
Other applications could relate to aerospace engineering.
For now, no super heroes.
THE OTHER RESEARCH- The University of Berkeley, California, is also looking for a new adhesive.
In an article in the American Chemical Society, Californian researchers presented an adhesive formed of microfibers like hair, which self-cleans itself from dust during movement over an area to ensure perfect and constant adhesion.
Medications: never with fruit juices.
Pay attention to the juice of grapefruit, orange and apple.
These drinks, consumed mainly in the summer because they are desalting and rich in vitamins, if associated with certain vital drugs, alter their absorption, amplifying or decreasing according to the case, their effectiveness, with even serious consequences for health.
David Nailey, a professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, recalls the risks of fruit juices, whether they are, in boxes or fresh, if they are associated with the ingestion of certain drugs; during the 236th national meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, he raises a new alarm: it is enough to reduce the risk of bruising.
Grapefruit juice has already been heavily criticized for being held responsible for increasing the effects of certain anti-arrhythmic, antibiotic, anxiolytic, anti-staminal and neurological drugs to toxic levels.
It is the Italian Medicines Agency itself, which gave the news in a two-year information bulletin, warning doctors and patients not to under-evaluate the danger arising from this mix and to pay attention to what they drink, if they take medicines such as Diazepam or Mezepam.
NOT COMPLETELY- According to experts, even orange and apple juice contains substances that inhibit drugs.
Long is the list of active ingredients inhibited by grapefruit and other juices.
Michele Carruba, director of the pharmacology department at the Public University of Milan, said: "These findings are in general, immediately reported to the various national and international drug agencies that will have to change the information notes of the drugs if necessary.
It is always necessary to read the illustrative papers of the drugs one is taking, and, if something is not clear, do not be impressed, but speak clearly to the doctor or pharmacist," said the expert to the agency Ansa.
The Nobel Prize in Economics to Paul Krugman.
The Nobel Prize in Economics was awarded to Paul Krugman for his research on business models and the location of economic activities.
Krugman, 55, is a New Keynesian who teaches at Princeton University and is also a famous New York Times columnist.
Krugman is one of the biggest critics of the Bush administration’s foreign policy and economic solutions.
A few months after the September 2001 attacks, during the days of Enron's bankruptcy, Krugman had written, in an article published in the New York Times, that the second event would have been more decisive than the first, in terms of consequences on the history of the United States.
A prediction that unleashed many controversies, and which was blamed on the economist for years, but which now turned out to be accurate.
“I’m surprised and even a little shocked at how quickly the memory of scandals such as the collapse of Enron or Worldcom has disappeared from the public’s attention,” Krugman said in late 2002.
According to Lorenzo Bini Smaghi of the European Central Bank’s executive committee, Krugman is a “high-value economist” but also a styled “disseminator” who is very aggressive, particularly critical of the Bush administration’s excesses of liberalism.
Open Office, the third edition of the "anti-Microsoft" package
This is the day of the release of OpenOffice.org.3.0, the open source personal productivity suite that aims to reach more and more users, from the home to the office, from professionals to the public administration, offering a free alternative to the most famous Microsoft Office.
After almost a year of work, carried out by voluntary developers, supervised by SUN Microsystem, the new Open Office package is shown to the general public with various new features: from the welcome screen, and the interface revised and became less austere, to other more important ones, such as the compatibility born for the standard operating system Apple Mac OS X format, and the latest version of the OS X.
Open Office paid particular attention to the interaction with the Office 2007 suite, and it is indeed possible to open documents with the new Microsoft extension (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx.)
Also interesting, some functions specific to certain modules, such as the one that reduces the dimensions of PowerPoint presentations, useful for example, to send them by e-mail, or to import PDF files into the graphic design module, retaining the original appearance of the page.
Always on this front, it is possible to create "Hybrid PDF" documents that combine the typical Adobe format graphic with the elements of a spreadsheet or text editor.
Collaboration between several people is an element that has had various improvements within the applications: in the spreadsheet, various users can intervene, avoiding conflicts over changes, in the development of texts, because each collaborator is assigned a comment color for better recognition in the revision phase.
Some companies are even working to bring certain OpenOffice features to the Web (on the cloud, on the cloud), and in the coming weeks, they are expected to release the final result.
The Italian version can be downloaded at http://en.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.html and is in addition to the English version that was on the mirror since Friday.
In addition to Windows and Mac OS, the suite is as usual also available for the Linux operating system.
On request, the installation CD can be shipped at home or at the workplace.
And if the theme of gratuity can be a way to spread it in homes, it is precisely in business, that Open Office next tries the great challenge, being already able to count on various projects carried out in the public administration and schools.
Not to mention the realities that offer a training, consultation and assistance service, ideal for small and medium-sized enterprises, which could also open up to business prospects.
Open Office consists of five main modules: Writer, for equivalent video writing of Word; Calc, is the spreadsheet that aims to replace Excel; Impress, for rival PowerPoint presentations; Dbase, like the famous Access, is the program that allows you to work on databases; finally Drwa is the graphical module.
Target for 2008, reach 5 million downloads, and considering that today we have almost 3 million and 600 miles, it is likely that with the release of the new version, we can even exceed the expected figure
