Students victims of expensive rents, up to 900 euros for a room.
The student housing market is not in crisis.
According to the latest Sunia survey, the renters' union, renting a single room can cost a student up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
"The phenomenon has now reached very serious aspects to the point of excluding entire categories of young people, from the right to study because of the very high global costs that families of origin must bear - explains the head of the study office of Sunia, Laura Mariani - in these cities, the high demand from students has so distorted the general process.
In most cases, rental offers also involve a series of violations: free contracts, unregistered, no rent limit, sub-leases.
For Sunia, extraordinary interventions through the revision of the tax are needed to calm prices.
Reading the survey in detail, we see that in Milan, for a bed in the Brianza zone, it takes about 450 euros; for a single room, we go from 650 euros minimum (Black Belt zone), to an average value of 800 (Lambiate zone, Udine, and Fiera) to a maximum of 900 euros (Vittoria zone)
In Florence, a bed costs on average, 350/400 euros, a room about 700 euros.
In Bologna, where students concentrate in the areas close to the University, it takes 250/280 euros for a bed in a double, and 370 to 500 euros for a single room.
In Rome, in the areas close to the central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna), one asks about 600 euros for a single, 450 for a bed in a double.
Slightly lower values (550 euros for a single) for areas close to other Universities (Ostiense and Cinecitt<0xC3><0xA0>).
You can save only if you move away in the peripheral areas:300 euros for a bed, and 450 for a single in the area Predestina, Centocelle or similar.
In Naples, for a bed you need 300/400 euros, for a single, you spend from 400 to 600 euros, with higher prices in the areas Policlinico, Vomero, and Colli Aminei.
In Bari, for a bed, it is necessary to count 250/350 euros, at least 350 for a single one.
In smaller cities, prices are lower in absolute terms, but they are of major importance in the urban economy.
Finally, cities such as Perugia, where rentals are often taken by extra-community students, have a further anomaly: the rent requested from foreign students is increased by 25/30% compared to that applied to Italians.
Farewell old cinema Paradiso, the cities elect the historic halls.
Historical cinemas are closing in favor of Multiplexes.
“A city without cinemas is a blind city, it’s like a face without eyes.”
The image presented by the director Giuseppe Tornatore, illustrates well what is happening in major Italian urban centers, but also in provincial cities,
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the birth on the periphery of large multi-chambers, and the death of consumption of mono-chambers in the central areas of cities, is one of the major events that seems inevitable and indisputable to us; it also has all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
To disappear, they are often historical places full of memory, "it's as if one of my friends always disappeared, someone we know is alive, with whom we shared a bit of path and so many emotions" observes the director of the Nuovo cinema Paradiso, film that offers to Tornatore the first Oscar of the 20 years ago and the first Oscar of the year.
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of merchants, mean everything: in the last five years, 316 cinemas of the traditional type have closed, and it is the rooms of the main cities that have mainly paid the costs: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closure, the Roman Emilia is at the top with 82 lost mono cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The evidence that confirms that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, because it is the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multi-room cinemas: 195 additional screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"Italian exploitation has developed irrationally," observes Paolo Protti, president of the Anec, "it is useful to build new structures, but we should still guarantee the survival of those that already exist, because when a room is closed in a city, these frequenters are not necessarily all willing to go to multiplexes.
Not to mention the lack of deliberation of credit in favor of merchants: the previous debt of the state is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful that, from an ethical and moral point of view, the Government does not respect existing laws.
To support the sector, it would take between 16 and 18 million euros per year.
The case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, worried about these closures, decided to resolve the situation through the signing of a protocol between the City Hall and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy, to defend and promote the cinemas mono rooms of the historic centers and on the outskirts.
Among the planned regulations, there are measures of tax facilities in favor of managers and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic area, and will have special rates for parking lots and in some parking lots.
"This is an initiative that I like," observes Giuseppe Tornatore "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by implementing other measures.
However, it is obvious that to contrast the super power of multiplexes, traditional rooms must also improve the quality of sound and image, because today's audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that for me, has always been important: the closure of the Supercinema de Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "New Cinema Paradiso" that I had already been thinking about for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass the Rialto, or the Quirinal of Via Nazionale, now closed, where I have lived so much shared emotions, I turn to the other side so as not to see the panels blackened by the dust.
