When the energy is born from the waves, now the big ones are launched.
This is an untapped deposit that occupies more than 70% of the planet’s surface and now the world’s major energy companies are discovering it.
Waves, currents, tides, these are the new renewable sources that giants like Chevron have laid eyes on, and are now trying to get their hands on.
The possibility of obtaining energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for hundreds of years, and in the 1970s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil fell, around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was put aside, but now the environmental authorities and the new increase in oil give a great rise to the sector
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15% of the world’s electricity needs could be covered by offshore wave operating systems.
This would be twice the amount produced by nuclear power plants.
And besides, there would be currents and tides.
Colossus on the attack.
The first company to focus on marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a facility in northern Portugal.
When the agreement was announced, it would have been a true revolutionary step.
Two years from now, more and more of these companies dedicated to traditional energy are relying on marine energy.
“Chevron is currently studying ocean energy technologies,” a spokesman for a company associated with the U.S. oil giant told the Wall Street Journal, “and it is evaluating opportunities to cooperate with us.”
The cooperation in question concerns the obtaining of a deliberate permit by the U.S. Energy Commission, necessary to give rise to a project for the exploitation of marine energy in Alaska.
This is a very interesting signal, especially if one considers that precisely in Alaska, the United States continues to extract oil, and recently President Bush has set up a project for further excavations.
In addition to Chevron, there are Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey, which are on the path of energy coming from the sea, and the amounts invested to date, although their details are not known, indicate, according to observers, a growing interest.
Technology to be developed.
Experts are talking about a technology still in its infancy, due to the fact that marine energy does not dispel fears of ecological impact.
At present, systems such as those in Portugal, or some in Scotland, are small in size, and do not seem to create major problems for the ecosystem.
To produce energy on a large scale, however, it is necessary to use technologies with a higher ecological impact.
And the choices are diverse: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of buoys connected to each other.
The thrust of the waves, which causes the mud to move up and down, is converted into a hydraulic pressure of the pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
The pressure rotates a turbine which in turn feeds a generator.
The energy is sent to the shore through submarine cables.
For now, we have four such systems in the project phase, pending a single federal approval and some of the energy could be used for a military installation.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces energy for a shopping mall and parking lot using six submarine turbines from New York’s East River.
The movement of water during the tides rotates the blades of the turbines, creating a rotational movement that feeds a generator.
Verdant has announced that it has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary authorizations to draw energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they say to the Institute for the Research of Electric Energy, deserves at this moment, the potential of the tides.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable than wind, sun, or waves, and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
And it is precisely on tidal energy that states such as New York, Maine and Alaska, along with others, look to the coast, invested $7.5 million in 2008 and expects investments of up to $35 million in 2009.
